subsection.p:
The common unit of heat, called \text{calorie (cal)}, is defined as the amount of heat needed to raise the temperature of 1\text{ g} of water by  1^\circ\text{C}  from  14.5^{\circ}\text{C} to 1 15.5^{\circ}\text{C} at 1\text{ atm}  of pressure, while the SI unit of the mechanical work is 1\text{ Joule (J)}.  The proportionality constant between the work and the thermal energy is presently known to be 4.1855\text{ J/cal}.

	1\text{ calorie} = 4.1855\text{ Joules}.\ \ \ \text{(mechanical equivalence)}

In engineering practice in the United States and the Great Britain, heat is also expressed in a unit called the British Thermal Unit or \text{BTU}.  One \text{BTU} is the amount of heat needed to raise the temperature of one pound of water by one degree Fahrenheit.  It is equal to 252\text{ calories}.

	1\text{ BTU} = 252\text{ calories}.\ \ \ \text{(units of heat)}


Note that nutrition professionals also use a unit of energy called \text{Calorie}, written with capital letter C, which is not the same as 1\text{ calorie}, written with a small letter c as  defined above, but instead 1000\text{ calories}.   

	1\text{ Nutrition Calorie} = 1000\text{ calories}.
